title: Grateful Dead Live at Winterland Arena on 1971-12-31
lineage: Dat (Sony PCM-R500) > Tascam DA-3000 (16-bit/48k) > Adobe Audition CC2015 >Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/
description:
Set 1

Dancin' In The Streets, Mr. Charlie, Brown Eyed Women, Beat It On Down The Line, You Win Again, Jack Straw, Sugaree, El Paso, Chinatown Shuffle, Tennessee Jed, Mexicali Blues, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Next Time You See Me, Playin' In The Band, Loser, One More Saturday Night*

Set 2

Truckin'-> Drums-> The Other One-> Me & My Uncle-> The Other One, Jam-> Black Peter, Big River, The Same Thing, Ramble On Rose, Sugar Magnolia, Not Fade Away-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Not Fade Away, E: Casey Jones

With Donna Godchaux * FM broadcast KSAN-San Francisco - Other artist(s): GD; NRPS; Yogi Phlegm

reviews.review_text:
That OLD same thing This is a solid show and it deserves a good listen by anybody who loves the band's music.

and Yes, i do believe Donna Jean is audible toward the very end of OMSN

I actually found the other One to be pretty bad assed 
It seemed like they were itching for it right out of Truckin'

Same Thing- Can't help but see this tune as a hybrid of Spoonful.
It seems a tad laborious for PigPen and this would  have been the weakest tune of his repertoire if he had brought it along to Europe.
In delivery the tune almost has a 'The Stranger'
feel to it at least as far as the vocal range Pigpen brings to the table.
I see how Weir would gravitate to Spoonful and then Same Thing when he got the blues fever in later years.

Also must say that Jerry's lead vocals during the second verse of Big River are shocking. 
I guess i am so used to it being a strictly Bob tune vocally.

Early 70’s Sweet Spot If March ‘71 and May ‘72 got married and had a baby it would sound like this show. The band is confident, creative and playful. I’ve moved this show up in my estimation and rotation over the years.
